bib.title: Total Kinetic Energy Release In The Fast Neutroninduced Fission Of 237Np

free_txt: Experiment was carried out at Weapons
Neutron Research of the Los Alamos Neutron Science
Center using the 15R beamline.
Compiled by S.H.
The 2E method was used to measure the fission product
masses and their TKE by detecting the fission
products and determining their energies after neutron
emission.
Fission fragment detector consisted of two
arrays of 3x3 Si PIN photodiodes placed inside
aluminum scattering chamber. The Si PIN photodiodes
(Hamamatsu S3590-09) arrays were placed on oposite
sides of the beam at angles of 65 deg and 115 deg
with respect to the incident beam. Each PIN diode had
an area if 1 cm2 and the arrays were placed 3.5 cm
from the actinide target.
Experiment was carried out at Weapons
Neutron Research of the Los Alamos Neutron Science
Center using the 15R beamline.
Neutrons were produced by spallation of thick
tungsten target by 800 MeV pulsed proton beam.
Primary neutron energy was determined by time
of flight. Proton beam consist of 625 mu-s long
macropulses with repetition rate of 100 Hz. Each
macropulse is composed of series of 250 ps wide
micropulses separated by 1.8 mu-s. Fission detector was
placed at a distance 13.85 m from the spallation
target. Time of flight of each interacting neutron was
measured using a timing pulse from a Si PIN diode and
the accelerator RF signal.
237Np target was prepared by vapor deposition of NpF4
on approx. 100 mu-g/cm2 thick carbon foil. Target has
an 1 cm radius and contained 34.2 mu-g/cm2 of (237Np)
F4. The target was tilted 45 deg with respect to
icident beam.
